In accordance with the use of ἀπείρατος Alford translates ‘ unversed in things evil ' 3 so Hofmann (‘B‹>·semfre7ml oder vom Uebeln unbem-offen, auf keinem Fall aber von Bb'sem oder zu Bbsem unversuclet oder unver- suclzbar’), Briickner, Erdmann. Others (Vulg. Aeth. Lutlier) give it an active sense, ‘God is not one who tempts to evil.' The latter interpretation would make the next clause (πειράζει δέ) mere tautology, and it has now no defenders. It seems to me that the case is equally strong against the former interpretation. The meaning of the rare word ἀπείραστος must be determined from the general force of πειράζω in the Nm, and especially from the following clause, which is evidently intended to be its exact correlative in the active voice (ἀπείρασ- τος; πειράζει δὲ αὐτός). The relation of the two clauses would have been more clearly marked if μὲν had been added after ἀπ.; compare for its omission J elf ξ 767, and below ii. 2, 11. Further it is impossible to read this sentence without being reminded of very similar phrases used about God by Philo and other post-Aristotelian philosophers, cf.
